column12: I do this every time I update a kernel.> > The 1st time I added ALSA
column13: I tried a non-root rpom build but the DEV things were not> made. Other than that
column14: I bet you could do non-root. The following can be scripted> easily.> > 1. get (a) alsa-drivers
column15: (b) alas-lib
column16: and (c) alsa-utils tarballs (if upgrading the> kernel then you probably have them from your last install).> 2. unpack them somewhere.> 3. for each of them
column17: go to the top directory of the unpacked tarball
column19: then look in (I'm going by memory) TOPDIR/utils/* you should see a spec> file there. Do this for the 3 tarballs and you get 3 spec files.> > 4. put the source tarballs in SOURCES and the spec files in SPECS
column23: doing>  "rpmbuild -ba SPECS/alsa-[X].spec; rpm -Uvh RPMS/i386/alsa-[X].rpm"> > 5. do that in order for the 3 spec files and you have just installed the alsa> drivers on your system. The 1st time you do this you need to put the correct stuff> in your modules.conf file (may take some research) then you get the alsa driver and> OSS compat capabilities
column24: or you can choose not to use the OOS compat stuff.> > Script making the spec
column27: and you have> "no-sweat" ALSA.> > NOTE: the (null) rpmbuild did take some tweaking
column28: it does a check for files in the> buildroot that you don't specify in your files section. In this case there is an> extra file (going by memory) "/include/sys/asound.h". Add a line at the end on the> "install" section of the spec file to delete that file and you are good to go.> > Gordon Messmer (yinyang@eburg.com) wrote*:> >> >On Fri

column1: Microsoft buys XDegress - more of a p2p/distributed data thing...I like this part - sounds like httpd on the client...http://www.openp2p.com/pub/a/p2p/2001/04/27/xdegrees.html"Once the Client Component is installed
column2: a server can order a program to runon the client. Any CGI script
column3: Java servlet
column4: ASP component
column5: etc. could berun on the client. This is like breaking the Web server into two parts.Originally
column6: Web servers just understood HTTP and sent pages. Then the fieldstarted demanding more from the Web and the servers got loaded down with CGIand mod_perl and active pages and stuff. So now the Web server can choose togo back to simple serving and (where the application is appropriate) let theclient do the other razzamatazz. This is superior to JavaScript in oneimportant detail: the program doesn't have to reload when a new page isloaded
column7: as JavaScript functions do.And because XDegrees uses Web-compatible technology
column8: users can accessXDegrees resources without installing any software
column9: simply by using theirbrowser."==="Scaling is the main question that comes to mind when somebody describes anew naming and searching system. CEO Michael Tanne claims to have figuredout mathematically that the system can scale up to millions of users andbillions of resources. Scaling is facilitated by the careful location ofservers (XDegrees will colocate servers at key routing points
column10: as Akamaidoes)
column11: and by directing clients to the nearest server as their default"home" server. Enterprise customers can use own servers to manage in-houseapplications.""Files can be cached on multiple systems randomly scattered around theInternet
column12: as with Napster or Freenet. In fact
column13: the caching in XDegrees ismore sophisticated than it is on those systems: users with high bandwidthconnections can download portions
column14: or "stripes
column15: of a file from severalcached locations simultaneously. The XDegrees software then reassemblesthese stripes into the whole file and uses digital signatures to verify thatthe downloaded file is the same as the original. A key component of thisdigital signature is a digest of the file, which is stored as an HTTP headerfor the file.	0

column1: Re: From salon.com - Forbidden thoughts about 9/11From nobody Mon Sep 15 17:59:27 2014Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-asciiI am delurking to comment on the Salon article. I just wanted to say that I am grateful they choose not to publish my forbidden thought. I sent it in a couple of days before the 9/11 commeration. If I had just watched the sentimental network and cable shows on 9/11 my cynical thoughts would have remain unchanged. However
column2: I watch the Frontline show "Faith and Doubt at Ground Zero" on PBS. That show tackled head on
column3: with much more courage than I have seen elsewhere
column4: the larger questions about good and evil
column5: about art as an alternate religion (Karlheinz Stockhausen -- 9/11 was a great work of art)
column6: and especially the question about how religion has a darker side which when carried to fanatic extremes tends to negate the humanity of the non-believers.I am not a religious person but I stunned at the scope of this program. It talked about the Lutheran minister who spoke at Yankees Stadium on a podium with other religious leaders present who was charged with heresy by his own church for promoting the idea that all religions are equal (presumably the Lutherans have the one true path?).Thanks for listening
column7: I just felt like I needed to put the word out about this program. My shallow comment on Salon and others like it (my boyfriend and I had sex while the towers collapsed) gives me pause about how some of us tend to harden ourselves to the suffering of others.Mike Chris Haun wrote:i though this was all rather interesting

column1: Kill Your GodsHindus mourn 'monkey god'By Omer FarooqBBC reporter in HyderabadHundreds of people have attended the funeral of a monkey which becamerevered as a divine incarnation of a Hindu god in the southern Indianstate of Andhra Pradesh.The monkey was quite old and both its hind legs were paralysedAnimal rights campaigners say the monkey died of starvation and exhaustionafter being trapped in a temple for a month by over-zealous worshippers.The animal was cremated in Anantapur district
column2: 400 kilometres (250 miles)south of the state capital
column3: Hyderabad
column4: on Sunday.It had not eaten for three weeks.Last rites were performed by priests in the village of Timmiganipally inthe presence of hundreds of devotees who had come to believe that themonkey was a reincarnation of the Hindu monkey god
column5: Hanuman.GarlandedOne animal rights activist said his group's efforts to save the monkey hadfailed because of the blind faith of the people.The monkey's death came a day after he and others tried to move the animalout of the temple
column6: but were prevented by villagers.The monkey
column7: which was found perched on top of an idol of Hanuman a monthago
